{'id': '2607.07420', 'categories': ['cs.RO', 'cs.HC'], 'pdf': 'https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.07420', 'abs': 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.07420', 'authors': ['Zhijin Meng', 'Francisco Cruz'], 'title': 'Initiation Safety: A Missing Dimension in Generalist-Robot Safety', 'comment': '4 pages, 2 figures. Accepted to RSS 2026 Workshop on Rethinking Safety for Generalist Robots', 'summary': "Safety for generalist robots is usually discussed in terms of motion or dialogue. We argue a third question is missing: should the robot take its first hard-to-undo social action at all, such as a greeting, an uninvited grasp, or stepping into someone's space? We call this initiation authorization. Current frameworks rarely treat it as a separate safety layer. Today's stacks often skip this step: a high engagement score or a confident VLA rollout is treated as permission to act. But seeing a person is not the same as having their consent to be addressed. We frame initiation authorization within generalist-robot safety and contrast it with post-plan VLA guardrails, implementing PAS (probe-authorize-speak) on a doorway humanoid, comparing it with direct-init on logged traces, and proposing a three-condition user study, with open questions on metrics, governance, and where initiation ends and foundation-model generation begins."}
